{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585388"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:10:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:10:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14964"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14964"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.31,0.46,0.13,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66456"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7652"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14964"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51907"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18715"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18719"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66456"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECell surface receptors play a crucial role in determining which cells a virus can infect, a property known as viral tropism. Different viruses recognise specific molecules on cell surfaces that act as attachment points.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following viruses primarily uses sialic acid receptors on epithelial cells for cellular entry?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rabies virus","Herpes simplex virus","Influenza A virus","Adenovirus","Hepatitis B virus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EInfluenza A virus\u003C/strong\u003E specifically recognises and binds to sialic acid residues on respiratory epithelial cells via its hemagglutinin protein. This interaction is crucial for viral entry and infection of respiratory tract cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other viruses use different receptors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERabies virus\u003C/strong\u003E uses nicotinic acetylcholine receptors for entry into neurons\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex virus\u003C/strong\u003E primarily uses nectin-1 and herpesvirus entry mediator receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenovirus\u003C/strong\u003E uses the coxsackievirus and adenovirus receptor\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B virus\u003C/strong\u003E enters hepatocytes using sodium taurocholate cotransporting polypeptide receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis receptor specificity explains the distinct patterns of infection and tissue tropism seen with different viral pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Influenza A virus uses sialic acid receptors on respiratory epithelial cells as its primary binding site","Different viruses target specific cell surface receptors which determines their tissue tropism","The specificity of viral receptors explains why certain viruses only infect particular cell types"],"references":["Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Pollard AJ, Bijker EM. A guide to vaccinology: from basic principles to new developments. Nat Rev Immunol. 2021 Fe